{"title_page": "Robot Zonda", "text_new": "{{short description|Rock band}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = \n| logotype        =\n| image           =\n| image_size      = 350px\n| background      = group_or_band\n| years_active    = 2006\u2013present\n| origin          = {{ARG}}, [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]]\n| genre           = [[Pop Rock]]\n| label           = Independent\n| current_members = [[Kiko Robot]]<br/>[[Mou Robot]]<br/>[[Paky Robot]]<br/>[[Guido Robot]]\n| URL             = [http://www.robotzonda.com.ar Official Website]}}\n\n'''Robot Zonda''' is a [[pop rock]] band, formed in 2006 at [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]], composed of [[Kiko Robot]] (vocals), [[Mou Robot]] (guitar), [[Paky Robot]] (drums), [[Guido Robot]] (bass).\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Formation ===\n''Robot Zonda'' was formed in 2006 at [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]] and keeps in activity at the present, performing hundreds of shows each year, both in their home town [[Buenos Aires]] and in other [[Rep\u00fablica Argentina|Argentina]] provinces and abroad.\n\n[[File:Robot Zonda Luna park.jpg|thumb]]\n\n=== National and International tours === \n\nFrom year 2009 on, ''Robot Zonda'' started to perform at lots of stages all across the country, visiting many times [[Ciudad de La Plata|La Plata city]], [[Mar del Plata]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]]. <ref>[https://www.facebook.com/events/809498782469273 Robot Zonda at Mendoza]</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/events/1374769982576768 Robot Zonda at Buenos Aires]</ref><ref>[http://www.conexionunder.com/notas/7393/robot-zonda-en-mendoza Robot Zonda at Mendoza (Conexi\u00f3n Under)]</ref>\n\nIn their hometown [[Ciudad de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires city]], they've played in important venues and festivals, like [[Luna Park]] performing as supporters of [[Deftones]], [[Niceto Club]], [[The Roxy Bar]], [[Ciudad Emergente]], [[Hot Festival]], etc. <ref>[https://open.spotify.com/album/3q6awbcABo0QDUFy6iG2my Robot Zonda's Luna Park Live Album]</ref> <ref>[https://www.allaccess.com.ar/event/the-roxy-rock-nights-robot-zonda-grace Robot Zonda at The Roxy Bar]</ref> \n\n''Robot Zonda'' also went on International tours, visiting [[Chile]] twice, playing a total of 5 shows in the neighbour country, including two shows in the popular Blondie discoth\u00e8que. Last year ''Robot Zonda'' performed in [[New York City]] for the first time. <ref>[http://192.cl/agenda/conciertos/robot-zona-vuelve-a-chile Robot Zonda Chile Tour]</ref><ref>[https://shockingwatts.tumblr.com/post/10720075415/robot-zonda-regresa-a-chile-para-realizar-4 Robot Zonda Chile Tour 2]</ref> <ref>[https://es-la.facebook.com/robotzondaoficial/photos/tbt-hoy-jueves-recordando-nuestro-show-en-estados-unidos-ac%C3%A1-la-puerta-de-ese-m%C3%AD/10157976579710329 Robot Zonda in New York City]</ref>\n\n\n=== MTV Latinamerica 09 Prize ===\nIn 2009, ''Robot Zonda'' was nominated for [[Anexo:Premios MTV 2009|MTV Latinamerica Prize 2009]], together with other 5 unsigned artists selected all across Latinamerica.<ref>[[:es:Anexo:Premios MTV 2009|Robot Zonda nominated for MTV Latinamerica Prize 2009]]</ref>\n\n=== Schools Tour ===\nIn the year 2009, ''Robot Zonda'' started a Schools Tour, performing live shows every day during 2 months in more than 44 schools at [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires City]]. The success of this idea, made ''Robot Zonda'' repeat the Schools Tour every year, including more schools and extending it to [[Provincia de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires Province]] too.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vpx80T6I5T4 Schools Tour Part 1]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rT5P7CjLeC4 Schools Tour Part 2]</ref>\n\n=== Main Shows ===\n\n''Robot Zonda'' has performed in several stages and festivals all across [[Argentina]]. Some of the main shows were at Hot Festival (with Catupecu Machu and Massive Attack among others), C\u00f3digo Pa\u00eds Festival (at [[Hip\u00f3dromo de Buenos Aires]]), \"PUMA Urban Art\" Festival (at Buenos Aires Design), S\u00f3nica Festival (at The Roxy and organized by Speedy, Telef\u00f3nica and Pop Art), \"Rock & Barrios\" Festival, XPOX (Extreme Sports Exposition), Ahora! Festival, Offside Festival (at Anfiteatro Mataderos), Ciudad Emergente Festival (at Centro Cultural Recoleta), \"Rock en el Rojas\" festival, \"3D Animation Rocks\" festival (at Centro Cultural Borges), 3 Groove, 3 Niceto, Sal\u00f3n Real, The Roxy (Los Arcos) and [[Plaza de Mayo]].<ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-hot-festival Robot Zonda at Hot Festival]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-groove Robot Zonda live at Groove]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-club-69-niceto Robot Zonda live at Niceto (Club 69)]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-the-roxy-los-ar Robot Zonda live at The Roxy (Los Arcos)]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-en-ciudad-emergente-jojo Robot Zonda live at Festival Ciudad Emergente]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-niceto Robot Zonda live at Niceto]</ref>\n\n=== Tribute song to Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez ===\n\nIn February 2013, ''Robot Zonda'' wrote a tribute song to the current box world champion, ''Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez''. The song had a big impact in specialized world press and was used by ''Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez'' himself to celebrate his 38th birthday.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TwA524X0RO8 Tribute Song to Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez]</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=488758714504581&id=367061049978240 Robot Zonda tribute song at Maravilla Martinez birthday]</ref><ref>[http://www.cdb.tv/maravilla-tiene-su-propia-cancion Robot Zonda tribute song to Maravilla Martinez in Mexican press]</ref><ref>[http://www.ciudad.com.ar/espectaculos/102874/maravilla-martinez-celebro-cumpleanos-propia-cancion Robot Zonda tribute song to Maravilla Martinez at Ciudad.com]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== EP ===\n* (2006) [[Robot Zonda (EP)]]\n\n=== \u00c1lbumes de estudio ===\n* (2010) [[Robot Zonda (First LP Album)]]\n* (2013) [[Uff (Robert Zonda album)|Uff]]\n\n=== Official Videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"center\"|Year\n!align=\"center\"|Song\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2008\n|align=\"left\"|Som\u00e1tico\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2010\n|align=\"left\"|Autobomba\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=2|2011\n|align=\"left\"|Ensue\u00f1o (Quiero Dormir)\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Romp\u00e9 Tu Ola\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=2|2012\n|align=\"left\"|Intravenosa\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Ser\u00eda Genial\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2013\n|align=\"left\"|Ac\u00e1 la fiesta empieza hoy\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.instagram.com/robotzonda Official Instagram]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/robotzondaoficial Official Facebook]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/robotzonda Official Youtube]\n* [https://twitter.com/robotzonda Official Twitter]\n\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Argentine rock music groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Rock band}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = \n| logotype        =\n| image           =\n| image_size      = 350px\n| background      = group_or_band\n| years_active    = 2006\u2013present\n| origin          = {{ARG}}, [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]]\n| genre           = [[Pop Rock]]\n| label           = Independent\n| current_members = [[Kiko Robot]]<br/>[[Mou Robot]]<br/>[[Paky Robot]]<br/>[[Guido Robot]]\n| URL             = [http://www.robotzonda.com.ar Official Website]}}\n\n'''Robot Zonda''' is a [[pop rock]] band, formed in 2006 at [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]], composed of [[Kiko Robot]] (vocals), [[Mou Robot]] (guitar), [[Paky Robot]] (drums), [[Guido Robot]] (bass).\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Formation ===\n''Robot Zonda'' was formed in 2006 at [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]] and keeps in activity at the present, performing hundreds of shows each year, both in their home town [[Buenos Aires]] and in other [[Rep\u00fablica Argentina|Argentina]] provinces and abroad.\n\n=== EP ===\nA short time after its formation, ''Robot Zonda'' released its first unsigned EP, called Robot Zonda and started to perform live in different stages in [[Buenos Aires]], and gave its first shows in other provinces, presenting its new songs. The main shows - those first years -  were \"Festival S\u00f3nica\" at The Roxy, Festival Ahora! (receiving an honorable prize from [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]] government, for its artistic quality and innovative sound), Festival PUMA Urban Art (with [[Tan Bi\u00f3nica]]) and XPOX (Extreme Sports Exposition).\n\nIn 2008, ''Robot Zonda'' released its first official video, from the song [[Som\u00e1tico]], belonging to its first EP. That video was aired in main music channels, like MTV, [[Much Music]] and [[Canal de la M\u00fasica]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ouhsld1tQCA First Official Video (Som\u00e1tico)]</ref>\n\n=== MTV Latinamerica 09 Prize ===\nIn 2009, ''Robot Zonda'' was nominated for [[Anexo:Premios MTV 2009|MTV Latinamerica Prize 2009]], together with other 5 unsigned artists selected all across Latinamerica.<ref>[[:es:Anexo:Premios MTV 2009|Robot Zonda nominated for MTV Latinamerica Prize 2009]]</ref>\n\n=== Schools Tour ===\nIn the year 2009, ''Robot Zonda'' started a Schools Tour, performing live shows every day during 2 months in more than 44 schools at [[Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires City]]. The success of this idea, made ''Robot Zonda'' repeat the Schools Tour every year, including more schools and extending it to [[Provincia de Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires Province]] too.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vpx80T6I5T4 Schools Tour Part 1]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rT5P7CjLeC4 Schools Tour Part 2]</ref>\n\n=== First LP Album ===\nAfter Schools Tour 2009 finished, ''Robot Zonda'' continued performing at different stages, while simultaneously recording their first LP album. That album would contain the same 5 songs that were included in Robot ZOnda (EP), together with 5 new songs. ''Robot Zonda's'' first album was released at the beginning of 2010 and had a big impact in local press, which covered not only the album release, but also the success of the recent Schools Tour 2009.<ref>[http://www.si.clarin.com/viento-falta-tuerca_0_408559150.html Robot Zonda interview at Clar\u00edn newspaper]</ref><ref>[http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1355625-la-ultima-banda-sonica Robot Zonda interview at La Naci\u00f3n newspaper]</ref>\n\nFirst album success between local press and ''Robot Zonda's'' public, took the group to the next step and made the album available at music stores all across [[Argentina]], Chile, [[Colombia]] and [[M\u00e9xico]]. Due to this, ''Robot Zonda'' increased their fan base and cleared the way for new shows at [[Buenos Aires]] provinces and at other countries.<ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/disquerias.php Robot Zonda \u2013 First Album Music Stores]</ref>\n\nAfter first album release, ''Robot Zonda'' filmed 5 official videos from songs in that album, between 2010 and 2012. All of them were aired at main TV music channels in [[Argentina]], Chile and [[M\u00e9xico]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hzXjqQa3ZxA Autobomba (Official Video)]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mTVjzvZBhGI Ensue\u00f1o (Quiero Dormir) (Official Video)]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gru9qJIBEJM Rompe Tu Ola (Official Video)]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1MMAh3gnh_s Intravenosa (Official Video)]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WScJWir8abU Ser\u00eda Genial (Official Video)]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-en-mtv Video Romp\u00e9 Tu Ola at MTV]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/autobomba-segundo-video-de-robot-zonda-rotando-en-vh1 Robot Zonda at VH1]</ref>\n\n=== National and International tours ===\nFrom year 2009 on, ''Robot Zonda'' started to perform at lots of stages all across the country, visiting many times [[Ciudad de La Plata|La Plata city]], [[Mar del Plata]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[San Mart\u00edn de los Andes|San Mart\u00edn]] and [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]].<ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-desembarco-por-primera-vez-en-la-ciudad-de-cordoba-argentina Robot Zonda at C\u00f3rdoba]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-se-presento-por-primera-vez-en-la-ciudad-de-mar-del-plata-argentina Robot Zonda at Mar del Plata]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-en-mendoza Robot Zonda at Mendoza]</ref><ref>[http://www.conexionunder.com/notas/7393/robot-zonda-en-mendoza Robot Zonda at Mendoza (Conexi\u00f3n Under)]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-en-la-ciudad-de-la-plata-argentina-para-2000-almas Robot Zonda at La Plata]</ref>\n\n''Robot Zonda'' also went on International tours, visiting [[Chile]] twice, playing a total of 5 shows in the neighbour country, including two shows in the popular Blondie discoth\u00e8que.<ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-tour-en-chile Robot Zonda first tour to Chile]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-en-chile-2011 Robot Zonda second tour to Chile]</ref>\n\n=== Main Shows ===\n\n''Robot Zonda'' has performed in several stages and festivals all across [[Argentina]]. Some of the main shows were at Hot Festival (with Catupecu Machu and Massive Attack among others), C\u00f3digo Pa\u00eds Festival (at [[Hip\u00f3dromo de Buenos Aires]]), \"PUMA Urban Art\" Festival (at Buenos Aires Design), S\u00f3nica Festival (at The Roxy and organized by Speedy, Telef\u00f3nica and Pop Art), \"Rock & Barrios\" Festival, XPOX (Extreme Sports Exposition), Ahora! Festival, Offside Festival (at Anfiteatro Mataderos), Ciudad Emergente Festival (at Centro Cultural Recoleta), \"Rock en el Rojas\" festival, \"3D Animation Rocks\" festival (at Centro Cultural Borges), 3 Groove, 3 Niceto, Sal\u00f3n Real, The Roxy (Los Arcos) and [[Plaza de Mayo]].<ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-hot-festival Robot Zonda at Hot Festival]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-groove Robot Zonda live at Groove]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-club-69-niceto Robot Zonda live at Niceto (Club 69)]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-the-roxy-los-ar Robot Zonda live at The Roxy (Los Arcos)]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-en-ciudad-emergente-jojo Robot Zonda live at Festival Ciudad Emergente]</ref><ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/robot-zonda-vivo-en-niceto Robot Zonda live at Niceto]</ref>\n\n=== Uff ===\n\nDuring 2012, ''Robot Zonda'' started recording its second studio album, named ''Uff'', which would contain 11 new songs and was launched on March 2013. Despite this, before releasing that album, ''Robot Zonda'' made an \"Uff Tour\", performing 25 live shows in only 3 months, introducing some of its new songs, that would be included in the new album.<ref>[http://www.robotzonda.com.ar/novedad/uff-tour-2012 Robot Zonda \"Uff Tour\"]</ref>\n\n=== Tribute song to Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez ===\n\nIn February 2013, ''Robot Zonda'' wrote a tribute song to the current box world champion, ''Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez''. The song had a big impact in specialized world press and was used by ''Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez'' himself to celebrate his 38th birthday.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TwA524X0RO8 Tribute Song to Sergio \"Maravilla\" Martinez]</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=488758714504581&id=367061049978240 Robot Zonda tribute song at Maravilla Martinez birthday]</ref><ref>[http://www.cdb.tv/maravilla-tiene-su-propia-cancion Robot Zonda tribute song to Maravilla Martinez in Mexican press]</ref><ref>[http://www.ciudad.com.ar/espectaculos/102874/maravilla-martinez-celebro-cumpleanos-propia-cancion Robot Zonda tribute song to Maravilla Martinez at Ciudad.com]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== EP ===\n* (2006) [[Robot Zonda (EP)]]\n\n=== \u00c1lbumes de estudio ===\n* (2010) [[Robot Zonda (First LP Album)]]\n* (2013) [[Uff (Robert Zonda album)|Uff]]\n\n=== Official Videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"center\"|Year\n!align=\"center\"|Song\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2008\n|align=\"left\"|Som\u00e1tico\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2010\n|align=\"left\"|Autobomba\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=2|2011\n|align=\"left\"|Ensue\u00f1o (Quiero Dormir)\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Romp\u00e9 Tu Ola\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=2|2012\n|align=\"left\"|Intravenosa\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Ser\u00eda Genial\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2013\n|align=\"left\"|Ac\u00e1 la fiesta empieza hoy\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.robotzonda.com.ar Official Website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/robotzondaoficial Official Facebook]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/robotzonda Official Youtube]\n* [https://twitter.com/robotzonda Official Twitter]\n\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Argentine rock music groups]]\n", "name_user": "Pablomoscatto", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robot_Zonda"}
{"title_page": "Captain Nemo", "text_new": "{{about|the fictional character}}\n{{short description|Character created by Jules Verne}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name        = Captain Nemo\n| series      = [[Voyages extraordinaires]]\n| image       = [[File:'Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea' by Neuville and Riou 027.jpg|245px]]\n| caption     = Nemo taking observations on the ''Nautilus''\n| first       = ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1870)\n| last        = ''[[Journey Through the Impossible]]''<br/>(1882)\n| creator     = [[Jules Verne]]\n| alias       = Prince Dakkar\n| gender      = Male\n| title       = Captain, Prince/Nobleman\n| spouse      = Deceased\n| children    = Deceased\n| relatives   = Deceased\n}}\n'''Captain Nemo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|i\u02d0|m|o\u028a}}, later identified as an East Indian, '''Prince Dakkar'''), is a fictional character created by the French novelist [[Jules Verne]] (1828\u20131905). Nemo appears in two of Verne's science-fiction classics, ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1870) and ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'' (1875). He also makes a cameo appearance in a play on which Verne may have collaborated, ''[[Journey Through the Impossible]]'' (1882).\n\nNemo is a mysterious figure. Though originally of unknown nationality, he's later described as the son of an East Indian [[Maharaja|raja]]. A scientific visionary, he roams the depths of the seas in his [[submarine]], the ''[[Nautilus (Verne)|Nautilus]]'', which was assembled from parts manufactured in several different countries, then shipped to Nemo's cover address. The captain is consumed by a hunger for vengeance and hatred of [[imperialism]]; the [[British Empire]] is ultimately revealed as his main antagonist. \n\nNemo has appeared in various film adaptations of Verne's novels, where he has been portrayed by such celebrated actors as [[James Mason]], [[Herbert Lom]], and [[Michael Caine]]. He has also been appropriated by other authors for their own novels, including [[Alan Moore]]'s ''[[The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen]]'', [[Philip Jos\u00e9 Farmer]]'s ''[[The Other Log of Phileas Fogg]]'',  [[Kevin J. Anderson]]'s ''[[Captain Nemo: The Fantastic History of a Dark Genius]]'', and [[Thomas F. Monteleone]]'s ''The Secret Sea''.\n\n== Etymology ==\n\n''Nemo'' is [[Latin language|Latin]] for \"no one\" or \"nobody\".\n\nMoreover ''Nemo'' is itself the Latin translation of [[Ancient Greek]] ''[[Outis]]'' (\"Nobody\"), the pseudonym adopted by [[Odysseus]], in [[Greek mythology]]\u2014a ruse employed to outwit the [[Cyclopes|Cyclops]] [[Polyphemus]]. This appears to be the intended meaning, since in ''The Mysterious Island'', when Cyrus Smith addresses him as Captain Nemo, the latter replies, \"I have no name!\"\n\n== Fictional character biography ==\n[[File:OrchhaPalace.jpg|thumb|[[Jahangir Mahal, Orchha|Jahangir Mahal]], home to the real-life rajas of [[Orchha State|Orchha]], Bundelkhand]]\n[[File:Nemo s death.jpg|upright|thumb|Captain Nemo's death in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'']]\nChief among the few details of Nemo's history given in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas'' are his hatred of imperialism and his grief over the loss of his loved ones in years past.\n\nIn ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'', Captain Nemo identifies himself as Prince Dakkar, son of the Hindu [[Maharaja|raja]] of [[Bundelkhand]], and a descendant of the Muslim [[Sultan]] [[Tipu Sultan|Fateh Ali Khan Tipu]] of the [[Kingdom of Mysore]], famous for the [[Anglo-Mysore Wars]] (1767\u20131799) and [[Mysorean rockets|Mysorean rocket]] technology. After the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]], in which Dakkar lost both his family and his kingdom, the prince devoted himself to scientific research, ultimately building the [[Nautilus (Verne)|''Nautilus'']] and crusing the seven seas with a crew of devoted followers. They gather [[bullion]] from various shipwrecks in the ocean, most notably from the hulks of the Spanish treasure fleet sunk during the [[Battle of Vigo Bay]]. Nemo claims to have no interest in terrestrial affairs but occasionally intervenes to aid people in distress, e.g.,  by giving salvaged treasure to participants in the [[Cretan Revolt (1866\u20131869)]] against the island's [[Ottoman Turks|Turkish]] rulers ... by saving (both physically and financially) a [[Sinhalese people|Ceylonese]] or [[Tamil people|Tamil]] pearl hunter from a shark attack ... by rescuing the castaways in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas'' ... and by covertly protecting another set of castaways in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]''.\n\nLike many actual [[Princely state|Indian princes]] of the era, Nemo had a Western education, during which, as he states, he spent his youth touring and studying throughout Europe. In his first meeting with Professor Aronnax and his companions, the three castaways speak to him in French, English, [[Latin]], and German; Nemo later reveals that he is fluent in all of these tongues. Aronnax praises the captain's French, noting that he \"expressed himself with perfect ease and without any accent.\" Relying on his intuition and knowledge of [[ethnology]], the professor concludes that \"there's southern blood\" in him but can't determine the captain's exact origin. The ''Nautilus''{{'s}} library, lounge, and art collections reveal that Nemo is intimately acquainted with European culture, plus that he's an accomplished performer on the [[pipe organ|organ]].\n\nNemo dies of unspecified natural causes on board the ''Nautilus'', docked permanently inside Dakkar Grotto on [[The Mysterious Island|Lincoln Island]] in the [[Oceania|South Pacific]]. Cyrus Smith, leader of the castaways whom Nemo protected, administered the last rites, then submerged the ''Nautilus'' in the grotto's waters.\n\n== Character ==\n[[File:20000 Nemo organ.jpg|upright|thumb|Captain Nemo playing the [[organ (music)|organ]], at which he was a master.]]\n\nNemo's characteristics are largely presented through the observations of Professor Pierre Aronnax, narrator of ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas''. At their first meeting, the professor remarks: \"Whether this individual was thirty-five or fifty years of age, I couldn't tell.\" He goes on to describe Nemo as a tall, self-contained man with a straight nose, broad brow, and wide-set eyes--\"certainly the most wonderful physical specimen I'd ever met up with.\" In ''The Mysterious Island'', the sixty-something captain sports a long white beard.\n\nHe avoids dry land, except when it's uninhabited, as with [[Antarctica]] and [[desert islands]]. In keeping with his contempt for the nations of the surface, he uses no products that are not marine in nature, be it food, clothing, furnishing, or even [[tobacco]]. Little is revealed about his political opinions except an almost maniacal hatred of oppression, with which he identifies all the [[imperialistic]] nations of the world. He therefore identifies himself with those oppressed, be they [[Cretan Revolt (1866\u20131869)|Cretans]] rising against the [[Ottoman Turks|Turks]], [[Ceylonese]] [[pearl hunting|pearl divers]], or even [[Right whale|black whales]] attacked by [[sperm whales|cachalots (sperm whales)]]. When Professor Aronnax alleges that Nemo violates maritime and international law by sinking warships, Nemo responds that he is merely defending himself from his attackers, and that the laws of the world on the surface no longer apply to him. In one scene, Nemo exclaims:\n\n{{quotation|On its surface they can still exercise their iniquitous claims, battle each other, devour each other, haul every earthly horror. But thirty feet below sea level, their dominion ceases, their influence fades, their power vanishes! Ah, sir, live! Live in the heart of the seas! Here alone lies independence! Here I recognize no superiors! Here I'm free!<ref>{{cite wikisource |last=Verne |first=Jules |translator=Frederick Paul Walter |title=20,000 Leagues Under the Seas |wslink=20,000 Leagues Under the Seas (Walter)/Chapter 10 |origyear=1870 |year=1991 |isbn=978-1-43844-663-9 |noicon=yes}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:20000 graveyard.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Captain Nemo standing over the crew of the ''Nautilus'' as they observe an underwater funeral]]\n\nNemo is devoted to his crew and grieves deeply when one is killed in the [[giant squid]] attack in the [[Caribbean Sea]], or after a midnight encounter with a surface ship. He shows the same compassion in his treatment of the castaways in ''The Mysterious Island'', and retains a strong attachment to his deceased wife and children. Though short-tempered, he rarely expresses his anger. He is also a man of immense courage, in the forefront of every activity, from releasing the ''Nautilus'' from the Antarctic ice to fighting squid in the Caribbean; and notable for having worked consecutive eight-hour shifts without a break, with little oxygen, to free the ''Nautilus'' from the ice. He was also identified as having discovered [[Atlantis]].\n\nAn extraordinary engineer, Nemo has designed and built the ''Nautilus'', besides inventing her electric propulsion and navigation systems. He has an exceptional mastery of underwater navigation, taking upon himself the most difficult submarine passages, such as those under the [[Suez|Isthmus of Suez]] and the Antarctic ice sheet.\n\n[[File:20000 Nautilus Salon.jpg|upright|thumb|The Grand Salon of the ''[[Nautilus (Verne)|Nautilus]]'']]\n\nHe has a comprehensive knowledge of [[marine biology]], and it is his respect for Professor Aronnax's expertise in the field which led to his befriending the professor when the latter was cast upon the ''Nautilus''. Further, he is said to have read and annotated all the books he possessed in the ''Nautilus''{{'s}} vast library.\n\nHe has very fine taste in art, possessing several masterpieces of both painting and sculpture, from ancient and modern European masters, all of which are housed in the Grand Salon of the ''Nautilus'', along with his collection of [[pearl]]s, [[coral]]s and other such marine products, which he had gathered himself. In the opinion of Professor Aronnax, the collection of the Grand Salon far outstrips that of the [[Louvre]]. Despite the opulence visible all through the ''[[Nautilus (Verne)|Nautilus]]'', Nemo's cabin was furnished with little beside a bed and the navigational instruments integral to the ''Nautilus''. Captain Nemo is believed to be extremely affluent, in that while he never states exactly how much he is worth, he claims that 'without missing it, he could pay the national debt of France'.  At the time of ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea''{{'s}} publication, this was worth 4.6 billion francs, or $18.4 billion U.S. dollars in 2018.\n\nNemo tells Professor Aronnax that his intention was to have his autobiography sealed in an unsinkable casket and thrown overboard by the last survivor of the ''Nautilus''{{'s}} crew, in the hope that it would be washed up somewhere. Accordingly an unsinkable casket does wash up in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'' (wherein is revealed Nemo's background story), containing tools, guns, navigation instruments, an atlas, books, blank paper, and even clothing. The crate is lashed to empty barrels, and the contents sealed in a waterproof zinc envelope, showing careful preparation and packing. Throughout the same book, Nemo acts as an agent of [[Divine Providence]], as when the sailor Pencroff laments the absence of [[tobacco]], and a hunting party discover a plant that the young naturalist Harbert identifies as such. The other castaways keep the discovery secret until they can dry and cure the leaves. One evening, Pencroff is offered some coffee by his friends. When he declines, they say, \"A pipe, then?\" and produce a homemade pipe stuffed full, with a coal to light it. Pencroff exclaims, \"O, divine Providence! sacred Author of all things!&nbsp;... Nothing more is now wanting to our island\".<ref>{{cite wikisource |last=Verne |first=Jules |translator=Agnes Kinloch Kingston |title=The Mysterious Island |wslink=The Mysterious Island/Part 2/Chapter 10 |origyear=1874 |year=1875 |noicon=yes}}</ref>\n\n== Emblem ==\n\nHis emblem, as given in a description of the flag he raised when claiming [[Antarctica]], is a large golden '''''N''''' on a black field. The motto of the ''Nautilus'' was ''Mobilis in mobili'', which may be roughly translated from Latin as, \"moving amidst mobility\", \"moving within the moving element\", or \"changing in the changes\".\n\n[[File:20000 mobilis in mobili.jpg|center|thumb|The [[motto]] of the ''Nautilus'']]\n\n== Origin ==\n\nIn the initial draft of ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'', Nemo was a [[szlachcic|Polish noble]], a member of the [[szlachta]], resenting the murder of his family during the Russian repression of the [[January Uprising]]; but Verne's editor [[Pierre-Jules Hetzel]] feared a book ban in the Russian market and offending a French ally, the [[Russian Empire]], and had Verne obscure Nemo's motivation in the first book.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Mike |last=Perschon |url=http://www.verniana.org/volumes/02/A4/Perschon.pdf |title=Finding Nemo: Verne's Antihero as Original Steampunk |journal=Verniana: Jules Verne Studies |volume=2 |date=February 1, 2010 |pages=181\u2013182}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Jess |last=Nevins |title=The Encyclopedia of Fantastic Victoriana |location=Austin, Texas |publisher=Monkeybrain Books |year=2005 |page=128 |isbn=978-1-93226-515-6}}</ref> In the second book of ''Twenty Thousand Leagues under the Sea'', Nemo comes close to revealing his Indian ancestry, though this is not obvious except in retrospect, where he saves a [[Sri Lanka|Ceylonese]] pearl-fisher in the [[Gulf of Mannar]].\n\n=== Chronological inconsistency ===\n\n''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea'' was written between 1869 and 1870 and records the voyages of the ''Nautilus'' between 1866 and 1868. ''The Mysterious Island'' was written in 1874 but is set immediately after the [[American Civil War]], from 1861 to 1865. This would mean that Captain Nemo who appeared in ''The Mysterious Island'' dies ''before'' Captain Nemo who appeared in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea'' sets out on the undersea travels. Also, when Captain Nemo is finally seen in ''The Mysterious Island'', he mentions having met Aronnax 16 years previously.\n\nMany errors in the original French first printing (the 'grand in-8' published by [[Pierre-Jules Hetzel]]) are likely the fault of the editors who, at that time, were unlikely to consult the authors of the books they edited before making a change.  According to the new, full translation put out by the [[Naval Institute Press]], nearly all errors can be attributed to the editors, with only a few being the fault of Jules Verne, who was otherwise meticulous.  The inconsistency of the dates between ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'' and ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'' is perhaps evidence in this argument, as it seems unlikely that Verne would make such an obvious gaffe.\n\nThe ''Nautilus'' goes down in the [[Maelstrom]] on June 2, 1868, according to ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea'', but may have survived. (''The Mysterious Island'' gives this date as June 22, 1867.) Captain Nemo dies on the ''Nautilus'' under Lincoln Island in ''The Mysterious Island'' on October 15, 1868. Therefore, some chronological inconsistencies still exist: Cyrus and Gideon knew of Captain Nemo years before Aronnax published his story, Nemo being trapped under Lincoln Island all during the time in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea''.\n\n== Portrayals ==\nIn most subsequent media adaptations of ''20,000 Leagues'' and ''Mysterious Island'', Nemo is (in a deviation from Verne's novels) depicted as a European. Actors who have played Nemo include:\n* [[Allen Holubar]] in ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1916 film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1916)\n* [[Lionel Barrymore]] (as Count Andre Dakkar) in ''[[The Mysterious Island (1929 film)|The Mysterious Island]]'' (1929)\n* [[Leonard Penn]] in the Columbia film serial ''[[Mysterious Island (serial)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1951)\n* [[Thomas Mitchell (actor)|Thomas Mitchell]] in the TV series ''[[Tales of Tomorrow]]'' (1952)\n* [[James Mason]] in the Walt Disney film ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1954 film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1954)\n* [[Herbert Lom]] in ''[[Mysterious Island (1961 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1961)\n* [[Robert Ryan]] in ''[[Captain Nemo and the Underwater City]]'' (1969)\n* [[Omar Sharif]] in ''[[La Isla misteriosa y el capit\u00e1n Nemo]]'' (1973)\n* [[Len Carlson]] in the animated series ''[[The Undersea Adventures of Captain Nemo]]'' (1975)\n* [[Vladislav Dvorzhetsky]] in the Soviet television miniseries ''[[Captain Nemo (miniseries)|Captain Nemo]]'' (1975)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Ferrer]] in the TV movie and short-lived TV series ''[[The Return of Captain Nemo]]'' (1978)\n* [[Akio \u014ctsuka|Akio Otsuka]] in the anime series ''[[Nadia: The Secret of Blue Water]]'' (1990\u20131991)\n* [[John Bach]] in the TV series ''[[Mysterious Island (TV series)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1995)\n* [[Michael Caine]] in the ABC-TV miniseries ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1997 Village Roadshow film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1997)\n* [[Ben Cross]] in the NBC TV movie ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1997 Hallmark film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1997)\n* [[Naseeruddin Shah]] in the film ''[[The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen (film)|The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen]]'' (2003)\n* [[Patrick Stewart]] in the TV movie ''[[Mysterious Island (2005 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (2005)\n* [[Sean Lawlor]] in the film ''[[30,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (2007)\n* [[W. Morgan Sheppard]] in the film ''[[Jules Verne's Mysterious Island (2010 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (2010)\n* [[Faran Tahir]] in the TV series ''[[Once Upon a Time (season 6)|Once Upon a Time]]'' (2016\u20132017)\n\n==In culture==\n[[Nemo (file manager)|Nemo]] is the official file manager for the [[Cinnamon (software)|Cinnamon]] desktop environment; the name plays off of the [[Nautilus (file manager)|Nautilus file manager]] from which it was forked.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinnamon.linuxmint.com/?p=198 |title=Introducing Nemo |first=Clement |last=Lefebvre |date=September 4, 2012 |accessdate=May 4, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622043748/http://cinnamon.linuxmint.com/?p=198 |archivedate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\nA Polish singer - Bogdan Gajkowski - popular especially during the 1980s, started recording song under the name \"Kapitan Nemo\" the Polish name of Captain Nemo.\n\nThe Japanese [[Otome game|otome]] [[visual novel]], ''[[Code: Realize \u2212 Guardian of Rebirth|Code: Realize- Guardian of Rebirth]]'', features a scientist named Nemo. Nemo created an airship named the ''Nautilus'' within the game. He considers the engineer Impey Barbicane, [[From the Earth to the Moon|a reference to another Jules Verne novel]], his ultimate scientific rival.\n\n== Images ==\n<gallery>\nFile:20000_Nemo_Aronnax_plans.jpg|Captain Nemo and Professor Aronnax discussing the plans of the ''Nautilus''\nFile:20000 Nautilus Nemo room.jpg|Captain Nemo's room aboard the ''Nautilus''\nFile:20000 Nautilus Library Nemo Aronnax.jpg|The library of the ''Nautilus''\nFile:20000 Nautilus engines.jpg|Engine room of the ''Nautilus''\nFile:Nemo Aronax viewbay diver.jpg|The encounter with the [[Cretan]] diver\nFile:20000 squid Nautilus viewbay.jpg|The commencement of the attack of the squids at the [[Bahamas]]\nFile:20000 squid Nautilus door.jpg|Captain Nemo fighting a giant squid aboard the ''Nautilus''\nFile:Nautilus wrecks.jpg|The silhouette of the ''Nautilus'' in the distance\nFile:Nautilus Ile mysterieuse.jpg|The ''Nautilus'' in Dakkar Grotto, as pictured in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]''\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170222074005/http://www.imdb.com/character/ch0027258/ Captain Nemo] on [[IMDb]]\n* [http://jv.gilead.org.il/kravitz/3/16.html ''The Mysterious Island'': The Secret of the Island: Chapter XVI]. A summary of his life.\n* [http://perso.wanadoo.fr/jules-verne/CIEH.htm Literary analysis of the novels of Jules Verne (In French)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110708144346/http://chilembwe.com/captain_nemo/origin.html The origin of Captain Nemo: at Captnemo's Home]\n* [http://nemo2017.com Published in 2017 a new, illustrated book of Jules Verne's classic sci-fi novel by UK artist G.M. Burley (limited runs)]\n\n{{Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea}}\n{{The Mysterious Island}}\n{{Pirates}}\n{{Jules Verne}}\n{{The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nemo, Captain}}\n[[Category:America's Best Comics characters]]\n[[Category:Characters in written science fiction]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1870]]\n[[Category:Fictional explorers]]\n[[Category:Fictional Indian people]]\n[[Category:Fictional mad scientists]]\n[[Category:Fictional pirates]]\n[[Category:Fictional princes]]\n[[Category:Fictional sailors]]\n[[Category:Fictional sea captains]]\n[[Category:Fictional undersea characters]]\n[[Category:Jules Verne characters]]\n[[Category:Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]\n[[Category:Once Upon a Time (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the fictional character}}\n{{short description|Character created by Jules Verne}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name        = Captain Nemo\n| series      = [[Voyages extraordinaires]]\n| image       = [[File:'Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea' by Neuville and Riou 027.jpg|245px]]\n| caption     = Nemo taking observations on the ''Nautilus''\n| first       = ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1870)\n| last        = ''[[Journey Through the Impossible]]''<br/>(1882)\n| creator     = [[Jules Verne]]\n| alias       = Prince Dakkar\n| gender      = Male\n| title       = Captain, Prince/Nobleman\n| spouse      = Deceased\n| children    = Deceased\n| relatives   = Deceased\n}}\n'''Captain Nemo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|i\u02d0|m|o\u028a}}, later identified as an East Indian, '''Prince Dakkar'''), is a fictional character created by the French novelist [[Jules Verne]] (1828\u20131905). Nemo appears in two of Verne's science-fiction classics, ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1870) and ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'' (1875). He also makes a cameo appearance in a play on which Verne may have collaborated, ''[[Journey Through the Impossible]]'' (1882).\n\nNemo is a mysterious figure. Though originally of unknown nationality, he's later described as the son of an East Indian [[Maharaja|raja]]. A scientific visionary, he roams the depths of the seas in his [[submarine]], the ''[[Nautilus (Verne)|Nautilus]]'', which was assembled from parts manufactured in several different countries, then shipped to Nemo's cover address. The captain is consumed by a hunger for vengeance and hatred of [[imperialism]]; the [[British Empire]] is ultimately revealed as his main antagonist. \n\nNemo has appeared in various film adaptations of Verne's novels, where he has been portrayed by such celebrated actors as [[James Mason]], [[Herbert Lom]], and [[Michael Caine]]. He has also been appropriated by other authors for their own novels, including [[Alan Moore]]'s ''[[The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen]]'', [[Philip Jos\u00e9 Farmer]]'s ''[[The Other Log of Phileas Fogg]]'',  [[Kevin J. Anderson]]'s ''[[Captain Nemo: The Fantastic History of a Dark Genius]]'', and [[Thomas F. Monteleone]]'s ''The Secret Sea''.\n\n== Etymology ==\n\n''Nemo'' is [[Latin language|Latin]] for \"no one\" or \"nobody\".\n\nMoreover ''Nemo'' is itself the Latin translation of [[Ancient Greek]] ''[[Outis]]'' (\"Nobody\"), the pseudonym adopted by [[Odysseus]], in [[Greek mythology]]\u2014a ruse employed to outwit the [[Cyclopes|Cyclops]] [[Polyphemus]]. This appears to be the intended meaning, since in ''The Mysterious Island'', when Cyrus Smith addresses him as Captain Nemo, the latter replies, \"I have no name!\"\n\n== Fictional character biography ==\n[[File:OrchhaPalace.jpg|thumb|[[Jahangir Mahal, Orchha|Jahangir Mahal]], home to the real-life rajas of [[Orchha State|Orchha]], Bundelkhand]]\n[[File:Nemo s death.jpg|upright|thumb|Captain Nemo's death in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'']]\nChief among the few details of Nemo's history given in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas'' are his hatred of imperialism and his grief over the loss of his loved ones in years past.\n\nIn ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'', Captain Nemo identifies himself as Prince Dakkar, son of the Hindu [[Maharaja|raja]] of [[Bundelkhand]], and a descendant of the Muslim [[Sultan]] [[Tipu Sultan|Fateh Ali Khan Tipu]] of the [[Kingdom of Mysore]], famous for the [[Anglo-Mysore Wars]] (1767\u20131799) and [[Mysorean rockets|Mysorean rocket]] technology. After the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]], in which Dakkar lost both his family and his kingdom, the prince devoted himself to scientific research, ultimately building the [[Nautilus (Verne)|''Nautilus'']] and crusing the seven seas with a crew of devoted followers. They gather [[bullion]] from various shipwrecks in the ocean, most notably from the hulks of the Spanish treasure fleet sunk during the [[Battle of Vigo Bay]]. Nemo claims to have no interest in terrestrial affairs but occasionally intervenes to aid people in distress, e.g.,  by giving salvaged treasure to participants in the [[Cretan Revolt (1866\u20131869)]] against the island's [[Ottoman Turks|Turkish]] rulers ... by saving (both physically and financially) a [[Sinhalese people|Ceylonese]] or [[Tamil people|Tamil]] pearl hunter from a shark attack ... by rescuing the castaways in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas'' ... and by covertly protecting another set of castaways in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]''.\n\nLike many actual [[Princely state|Indian princes]] of the era, Nemo had a Western education, during which, as he states, he spent his youth touring and studying throughout Europe. In his first meeting with Professor Aronnax and his companions, the three castaways speak to him in French, English, [[Latin]], and German; Nemo later reveals that he is fluent in all of these tongues. Aronnax praises the captain's French, noting that he \"expressed himself with perfect ease and without any accent.\" Relying on his intuition and knowledge of [[ethnology]], the professor concludes that \"there's southern blood\" in him but can't determine the captain's exact origin. The ''Nautilus''{{'s}} library, lounge, and art collections reveal that Nemo is intimately acquainted with European culture, plus that he's an accomplished performer on the [[pipe organ|organ]].\n\nNemo dies of unspecified natural causes on board the ''Nautilus'', docked permanently inside Dakkar Grotto on [[The Mysterious Island|Lincoln Island]] in the [[Oceania|South Pacific]]. Cyrus Smith, leader of the castaways whom Nemo protected, administered the last rites, then submerged the ''Nautilus'' in the grotto's waters.\n\n== Character ==\n[[File:20000 Nemo organ.jpg|upright|thumb|Captain Nemo playing the [[organ (music)|organ]], at which he was a master.]]\n\nNemo's character in the novels is largely seen through the observations of Professor Pierre Aronnax, the narrator of ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea'', when Nemo is about forty years of age and described as a reticent man, tall and swarthy in appearance, with a straight nose and wide-set eyes. In ''The Mysterious Island'', the aged Captain Nemo sports a long white beard.\n\nHe avoids dry land, except when it's uninhabited, as with [[Antarctica]] and [[desert islands]]. In keeping with his contempt for the nations of the surface, he uses no products that are not marine in nature, be it food, clothing, furnishing, or even [[tobacco]]. Little is revealed about his political opinions except an almost maniacal hatred of oppression, with which he identifies all the [[imperialistic]] nations of the world. He therefore identifies himself with those oppressed, be they [[Cretan Revolt (1866\u20131869)|Cretans]] rising against the [[Ottoman Turks|Turks]], [[Ceylonese]] [[pearl hunting|pearl divers]], or even [[Right whale|black whales]] attacked by [[sperm whales|cachalots (sperm whales)]]. When Professor Aronnax alleges that Nemo violates maritime and international law by sinking warships, Nemo responds that he is merely defending himself from his attackers, and that the laws of the world on the surface no longer apply to him. In one scene, Nemo exclaims:\n\n{{quotation|On its surface they can still exercise their iniquitous claims, battle each other, devour each other, haul every earthly horror. But thirty feet below sea level, their dominion ceases, their influence fades, their power vanishes! Ah, sir, live! Live in the heart of the seas! Here alone lies independence! Here I recognize no superiors! Here I'm free!<ref>{{cite wikisource |last=Verne |first=Jules |translator=Frederick Paul Walter |title=20,000 Leagues Under the Seas |wslink=20,000 Leagues Under the Seas (Walter)/Chapter 10 |origyear=1870 |year=1991 |isbn=978-1-43844-663-9 |noicon=yes}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:20000 graveyard.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Captain Nemo standing over the crew of the ''Nautilus'' as they observe an underwater funeral]]\n\nNemo is devoted to his crew and grieves deeply when one is killed in the [[giant squid]] attack in the [[Caribbean Sea]], or after a midnight encounter with a surface ship. He shows the same compassion in his treatment of the castaways in ''The Mysterious Island'', and retains a strong attachment to his deceased wife and children. Though short-tempered, he rarely expresses his anger. He is also a man of immense courage, in the forefront of every activity, from releasing the ''Nautilus'' from the Antarctic ice to fighting squid in the Caribbean; and notable for having worked consecutive eight-hour shifts without a break, with little oxygen, to free the ''Nautilus'' from the ice. He was also identified as having discovered [[Atlantis]].\n\nAn extraordinary engineer, Nemo has designed and built the ''Nautilus'', besides inventing her electric propulsion and navigation systems. He has an exceptional mastery of underwater navigation, taking upon himself the most difficult submarine passages, such as those under the [[Suez|Isthmus of Suez]] and the Antarctic ice sheet.\n\n[[File:20000 Nautilus Salon.jpg|upright|thumb|The Grand Salon of the ''[[Nautilus (Verne)|Nautilus]]'']]\n\nHe has a comprehensive knowledge of [[marine biology]], and it is his respect for Professor Aronnax's expertise in the field which led to his befriending the professor when the latter was cast upon the ''Nautilus''. Further, he is said to have read and annotated all the books he possessed in the ''Nautilus''{{'s}} vast library.\n\nHe has very fine taste in art, possessing several masterpieces of both painting and sculpture, from ancient and modern European masters, all of which are housed in the Grand Salon of the ''Nautilus'', along with his collection of [[pearl]]s, [[coral]]s and other such marine products, which he had gathered himself. In the opinion of Professor Aronnax, the collection of the Grand Salon far outstrips that of the [[Louvre]]. Despite the opulence visible all through the ''[[Nautilus (Verne)|Nautilus]]'', Nemo's cabin was furnished with little beside a bed and the navigational instruments integral to the ''Nautilus''. Captain Nemo is believed to be extremely affluent, in that while he never states exactly how much he is worth, he claims that 'without missing it, he could pay the national debt of France'.  At the time of ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea''{{'s}} publication, this was worth 4.6 billion francs, or $18.4 billion U.S. dollars in 2018.\n\nNemo tells Professor Aronnax that his intention was to have his autobiography sealed in an unsinkable casket and thrown overboard by the last survivor of the ''Nautilus''{{'s}} crew, in the hope that it would be washed up somewhere. Accordingly an unsinkable casket does wash up in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'' (wherein is revealed Nemo's background story), containing tools, guns, navigation instruments, an atlas, books, blank paper, and even clothing. The crate is lashed to empty barrels, and the contents sealed in a waterproof zinc envelope, showing careful preparation and packing. Throughout the same book, Nemo acts as an agent of [[Divine Providence]], as when the sailor Pencroff laments the absence of [[tobacco]], and a hunting party discover a plant that the young naturalist Harbert identifies as such. The other castaways keep the discovery secret until they can dry and cure the leaves. One evening, Pencroff is offered some coffee by his friends. When he declines, they say, \"A pipe, then?\" and produce a homemade pipe stuffed full, with a coal to light it. Pencroff exclaims, \"O, divine Providence! sacred Author of all things!&nbsp;... Nothing more is now wanting to our island\".<ref>{{cite wikisource |last=Verne |first=Jules |translator=Agnes Kinloch Kingston |title=The Mysterious Island |wslink=The Mysterious Island/Part 2/Chapter 10 |origyear=1874 |year=1875 |noicon=yes}}</ref>\n\n== Emblem ==\n\nHis emblem, as given in a description of the flag he raised when claiming [[Antarctica]], is a large golden '''''N''''' on a black field. The motto of the ''Nautilus'' was ''Mobilis in mobili'', which may be roughly translated from Latin as, \"moving amidst mobility\", \"moving within the moving element\", or \"changing in the changes\".\n\n[[File:20000 mobilis in mobili.jpg|center|thumb|The [[motto]] of the ''Nautilus'']]\n\n== Origin ==\n\nIn the initial draft of ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'', Nemo was a [[szlachcic|Polish noble]], a member of the [[szlachta]], resenting the murder of his family during the Russian repression of the [[January Uprising]]; but Verne's editor [[Pierre-Jules Hetzel]] feared a book ban in the Russian market and offending a French ally, the [[Russian Empire]], and had Verne obscure Nemo's motivation in the first book.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Mike |last=Perschon |url=http://www.verniana.org/volumes/02/A4/Perschon.pdf |title=Finding Nemo: Verne's Antihero as Original Steampunk |journal=Verniana: Jules Verne Studies |volume=2 |date=February 1, 2010 |pages=181\u2013182}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Jess |last=Nevins |title=The Encyclopedia of Fantastic Victoriana |location=Austin, Texas |publisher=Monkeybrain Books |year=2005 |page=128 |isbn=978-1-93226-515-6}}</ref> In the second book of ''Twenty Thousand Leagues under the Sea'', Nemo comes close to revealing his Indian ancestry, though this is not obvious except in retrospect, where he saves a [[Sri Lanka|Ceylonese]] pearl-fisher in the [[Gulf of Mannar]].\n\n=== Chronological inconsistency ===\n\n''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea'' was written between 1869 and 1870 and records the voyages of the ''Nautilus'' between 1866 and 1868. ''The Mysterious Island'' was written in 1874 but is set immediately after the [[American Civil War]], from 1861 to 1865. This would mean that Captain Nemo who appeared in ''The Mysterious Island'' dies ''before'' Captain Nemo who appeared in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea'' sets out on the undersea travels. Also, when Captain Nemo is finally seen in ''The Mysterious Island'', he mentions having met Aronnax 16 years previously.\n\nMany errors in the original French first printing (the 'grand in-8' published by [[Pierre-Jules Hetzel]]) are likely the fault of the editors who, at that time, were unlikely to consult the authors of the books they edited before making a change.  According to the new, full translation put out by the [[Naval Institute Press]], nearly all errors can be attributed to the editors, with only a few being the fault of Jules Verne, who was otherwise meticulous.  The inconsistency of the dates between ''[[Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]'' and ''[[The Mysterious Island]]'' is perhaps evidence in this argument, as it seems unlikely that Verne would make such an obvious gaffe.\n\nThe ''Nautilus'' goes down in the [[Maelstrom]] on June 2, 1868, according to ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea'', but may have survived. (''The Mysterious Island'' gives this date as June 22, 1867.) Captain Nemo dies on the ''Nautilus'' under Lincoln Island in ''The Mysterious Island'' on October 15, 1868. Therefore, some chronological inconsistencies still exist: Cyrus and Gideon knew of Captain Nemo years before Aronnax published his story, Nemo being trapped under Lincoln Island all during the time in ''Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea''.\n\n== Portrayals ==\nIn most subsequent media adaptations of ''20,000 Leagues'' and ''Mysterious Island'', Nemo is (in a deviation from Verne's novels) depicted as a European. Actors who have played Nemo include:\n* [[Allen Holubar]] in ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1916 film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1916)\n* [[Lionel Barrymore]] (as Count Andre Dakkar) in ''[[The Mysterious Island (1929 film)|The Mysterious Island]]'' (1929)\n* [[Leonard Penn]] in the Columbia film serial ''[[Mysterious Island (serial)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1951)\n* [[Thomas Mitchell (actor)|Thomas Mitchell]] in the TV series ''[[Tales of Tomorrow]]'' (1952)\n* [[James Mason]] in the Walt Disney film ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1954 film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1954)\n* [[Herbert Lom]] in ''[[Mysterious Island (1961 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1961)\n* [[Robert Ryan]] in ''[[Captain Nemo and the Underwater City]]'' (1969)\n* [[Omar Sharif]] in ''[[La Isla misteriosa y el capit\u00e1n Nemo]]'' (1973)\n* [[Len Carlson]] in the animated series ''[[The Undersea Adventures of Captain Nemo]]'' (1975)\n* [[Vladislav Dvorzhetsky]] in the Soviet television miniseries ''[[Captain Nemo (miniseries)|Captain Nemo]]'' (1975)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Ferrer]] in the TV movie and short-lived TV series ''[[The Return of Captain Nemo]]'' (1978)\n* [[Akio \u014ctsuka|Akio Otsuka]] in the anime series ''[[Nadia: The Secret of Blue Water]]'' (1990\u20131991)\n* [[John Bach]] in the TV series ''[[Mysterious Island (TV series)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1995)\n* [[Michael Caine]] in the ABC-TV miniseries ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1997 Village Roadshow film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1997)\n* [[Ben Cross]] in the NBC TV movie ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1997 Hallmark film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (1997)\n* [[Naseeruddin Shah]] in the film ''[[The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen (film)|The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen]]'' (2003)\n* [[Patrick Stewart]] in the TV movie ''[[Mysterious Island (2005 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (2005)\n* [[Sean Lawlor]] in the film ''[[30,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]'' (2007)\n* [[W. Morgan Sheppard]] in the film ''[[Jules Verne's Mysterious Island (2010 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (2010)\n* [[Faran Tahir]] in the TV series ''[[Once Upon a Time (season 6)|Once Upon a Time]]'' (2016\u20132017)\n\n==In culture==\n[[Nemo (file manager)|Nemo]] is the official file manager for the [[Cinnamon (software)|Cinnamon]] desktop environment; the name plays off of the [[Nautilus (file manager)|Nautilus file manager]] from which it was forked.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinnamon.linuxmint.com/?p=198 |title=Introducing Nemo |first=Clement |last=Lefebvre |date=September 4, 2012 |accessdate=May 4, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622043748/http://cinnamon.linuxmint.com/?p=198 |archivedate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\nA Polish singer - Bogdan Gajkowski - popular especially during the 1980s, started recording song under the name \"Kapitan Nemo\" the Polish name of Captain Nemo.\n\nThe Japanese [[Otome game|otome]] [[visual novel]], ''[[Code: Realize \u2212 Guardian of Rebirth|Code: Realize- Guardian of Rebirth]]'', features a scientist named Nemo. Nemo created an airship named the ''Nautilus'' within the game. He considers the engineer Impey Barbicane, [[From the Earth to the Moon|a reference to another Jules Verne novel]], his ultimate scientific rival.\n\n== Images ==\n<gallery>\nFile:20000_Nemo_Aronnax_plans.jpg|Captain Nemo and Professor Aronnax discussing the plans of the ''Nautilus''\nFile:20000 Nautilus Nemo room.jpg|Captain Nemo's room aboard the ''Nautilus''\nFile:20000 Nautilus Library Nemo Aronnax.jpg|The library of the ''Nautilus''\nFile:20000 Nautilus engines.jpg|Engine room of the ''Nautilus''\nFile:Nemo Aronax viewbay diver.jpg|The encounter with the [[Cretan]] diver\nFile:20000 squid Nautilus viewbay.jpg|The commencement of the attack of the squids at the [[Bahamas]]\nFile:20000 squid Nautilus door.jpg|Captain Nemo fighting a giant squid aboard the ''Nautilus''\nFile:Nautilus wrecks.jpg|The silhouette of the ''Nautilus'' in the distance\nFile:Nautilus Ile mysterieuse.jpg|The ''Nautilus'' in Dakkar Grotto, as pictured in ''[[The Mysterious Island]]''\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170222074005/http://www.imdb.com/character/ch0027258/ Captain Nemo] on [[IMDb]]\n* [http://jv.gilead.org.il/kravitz/3/16.html ''The Mysterious Island'': The Secret of the Island: Chapter XVI]. A summary of his life.\n* [http://perso.wanadoo.fr/jules-verne/CIEH.htm Literary analysis of the novels of Jules Verne (In French)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110708144346/http://chilembwe.com/captain_nemo/origin.html The origin of Captain Nemo: at Captnemo's Home]\n* [http://nemo2017.com Published in 2017 a new, illustrated book of Jules Verne's classic sci-fi novel by UK artist G.M. Burley (limited runs)]\n\n{{Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea}}\n{{The Mysterious Island}}\n{{Pirates}}\n{{Jules Verne}}\n{{The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nemo, Captain}}\n[[Category:America's Best Comics characters]]\n[[Category:Characters in written science fiction]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1870]]\n[[Category:Fictional explorers]]\n[[Category:Fictional Indian people]]\n[[Category:Fictional mad scientists]]\n[[Category:Fictional pirates]]\n[[Category:Fictional princes]]\n[[Category:Fictional sailors]]\n[[Category:Fictional sea captains]]\n[[Category:Fictional undersea characters]]\n[[Category:Jules Verne characters]]\n[[Category:Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea]]\n[[Category:Once Upon a Time (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in literature]]\n", "name_user": "F p walter", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Captain_Nemo"}
{"title_page": "2020 Atlanta Falcons season", "text_new": "{{short description|55th season in franchise history}}\n{{Infobox NFL_season\n| team            = Atlanta Falcons\n| logo            = Atlanta Falcons wordmark.svg\n| year            = 2020\n| record          =\n| division_place  =\n| coach           = [[Dan Quinn (American football)|Dan Quinn]]\n| owner           = [[Arthur Blank]]\n| general manager = [[Thomas Dimitroff]]\n| stadium         = [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]]\n| playoffs        =\n| pro bowlers     =\n| uniform         = Atlanta falcons unif20.png\n| shortnavlink    = Falcons seasons\n}}\nThe [[2020 NFL season|2020 season]] will be the [[Atlanta Falcons]]' upcoming 55th season in the [[National Football League]], their fourth playing their home games at [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] and their sixth under [[List of Atlanta Falcons head coaches|head coach]] [[Dan Quinn (American football)|Dan Quinn]].\n\nFor the first time since the [[2003 Atlanta Falcons season|2003 season]], the Falcons will be sporting new uniforms, which were unveiled on April 8, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlantafalcons.com/new-uniforms-2020|title=Official Website of the Atlanta Falcons Football Club|website=www.atlantafalcons.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe Falcons will attempt to improve on their [[2019 Atlanta Falcons season|7\u20139 season]] from the previous year and make the playoffs for the first time since [[2017 Atlanta Falcons season|2017]].\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Draft==\n{{main|2020 NFL Draft}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Atlanta Falcons|year=2020|border=2}}\"| 2020 Atlanta Falcons Draft\n|-\n! Round !! Selection !! Player !! Position !! College !! Notes\n|-\n! [[List of Atlanta Falcons first-round draft picks|1]] ||16\n| <!--PLAYER--> || <!--POSITION--> || <!--COLLEGE--> || <!--NOTES-->\n|-\n! 2 || 47\n| <!--PLAYER--> || <!--POSITION--> || <!--COLLEGE--> || <!--NOTES-->\n|-\n! 3 || 